*   Other (5.80%)

[[Prominent languages spoken by district]]

The official languages of Chhattisgarh are both [Modern Standard Hindi](/Modern_Standard_Hindi) and [Chhattisgarhi](/Chhattisgarhi_language). Both are classified as [Central Indo-Aryan languages](/Central_Indo-Aryan_languages), forming an integral part of what is broadly known as the [Hindi Belt](/Hindi_Belt). [Chhattisgarhi](/Chhattisgarhi_language) is not merely spoken but deeply understood by the vast majority of the population in Chhattisgarh, particularly dominating the central Chhattisgarh plain, where its cultural roots run deepest. Among tribals, [Chhattisgarhi](/Chhattisgarhi_language) is often referred to as *Khaltahi*, and in relation to [Odia](/Odia_language) speakers, it is known as *Laria*. [Chhattisgarhi](/Chhattisgarhi_language) itself is a vibrant linguistic entity, divided into numerous dialects, with [Surgujia](/Surgujia_dialect) from the [Surguja region](/Surguja_division) being so distinct that it is sometimes considered a language in its own right. Near the border with [Uttar Pradesh](/Uttar_Pradesh), this dialect seamlessly merges into [Bhojpuri](/Bhojpuri_language), while closer to the [Madhya Pradesh](/Madhya_Pradesh) border, it transitions into [Bagheli](/Bagheli_language). [Surgujia](/Surgujia_dialect) also blends with [Sadri](/Sadri_language) in the northeast, along the boundary with [Jharkhand](/Jharkhand). [Modern Standard Hindi](/Modern_Standard_Hindi) is widely spoken by migrants from outside the state and serves as a major language in urban centers and industrial areas. It's a common, if slightly misleading, phenomenon that many whose mother tongue is actually [Chhattisgarhi](/Chhattisgarhi_language) choose to record their speech as "Hindi" in census reports. [Odia](/Odia_language) is also extensively spoken in eastern Chhattisgarh, particularly in areas bordering [Odisha](/Odisha), reflecting historical and cultural ties. Minorities speaking Telugu and Marathi can be found along the respective borders with [Telangana](/Telangana) and [Maharashtra](/Maharashtra), further enriching the state's linguistic diversity. In the eastern [Bastar region](/Bastar_Division), [Halbi](/Halbi_language) and [Bhatri](/Bhatri_language) are prominent indigenous languages.

Beyond these more widely spoken tongues, Chhattisgarh is a repository of several truly indigenous languages. [Kurukh](/Kurukh_language) and [Korwa](/Korwa_language) are both spoken in the [Surguja region](/Surguja_division), each carrying the unique cultural heritage of its speakers. [Gondi](/Gondi_language) is a major language in southern Chhattisgarh, particularly prevalent in [Bastar](/Bastar_district) and its adjoining districts, serving as a vital link to the tribal identity of the [Gondi people](/Gondi_people). [Gondi](/Gondi_language) itself encompasses many dialects, such as [Muria](/Muria_language) in north [Bastar](/Bastar_district), which gradually transitions into [Madia](/Madiya_language) further south, and Dorli, a transitional dialect between [Gondi](/Gondi_language) and [Koya](/Koya_language), found along the borders of [Andhra Pradesh](/Andhra_Pradesh) and [Telangana](/Telangana). However, a regrettable trend is observed: most [Gonds](/Gondi_people) in the north and east of [Bastar](/Bastar_district), as well as in other parts of the state, have increasingly adopted regional languages, leading to a gradual, often irreversible, forgetting of their original tongue. [101](/District_-_North_Baster,_Kanker) [102](/District-Bastar,_Chhattishgarh) [103](/Language_in_India) [104](/BASTAR_REGION) It seems even languages, like ancient forts, can succumb to the relentless march of time and cultural assimilation.

### Gender ratio

Chhattisgarh exhibits a notably high female-to-male [sex ratio](/Human_sex_ratio) of 991 females per 1,000 males, a figure that positions it commendably at the fifth rank among the [states of India](/States_and_union_territories_of_India). This ratio is particularly significant because, despite being numerically smaller than some other states, Chhattisgarh is the 10th-largest state in [India](/India), making its balanced gender demographic a unique and positive indicator. [105](/Chhattisgarh,_At_a_glance)

The trend of the gender ratio (number of females per 1,000 males) in Chhattisgarh throughout the 20th century, while showing some fluctuation, has been one of gradual decline. However, a conspicuous and consistent pattern is that Chhattisgarh has *always* maintained a better female-to-male ratio compared to the national average, a historical anomaly that invites deeper sociological inquiry.

